Where's the Terry Hall sticky?
The lead singer of The Specials Terry Hall has died at the age of 63 following a "brief illness", the group has announced.
Singer-songwriter Hall rose to fame as part of the band, who were pioneers of the ska scene in the UK.

The Specials were formed in Hall's home city of Coventry in 1977, by Jerry Dammers, Lynval Golding and Horace Panter - with Hall, Neville Staple, Roddy Byers and John Bradbury joining a year later.

The band were originally called The Automatics, before changing their name to The Coventry Automatics, The Specials AKA The Automatics and finally, in 1978, settling on The Specials.
The band made a name with their ska and rocksteady style, and for providing a musical backdrop to economic recession, urban decay and societal fracture in the early 1980s.

They went produce a string of hits including A Message to You, Rudy, Do Nothing and Ghost Town, which spent three weeks at number one.

I was only there for the first night, see, but them cats at Impulse! just made my life complete. They put out four CDs of all that sound ‘Trane put out those nights. But you know my type, man. Can’t afford to eat, let alone spend some heavy cash on music. So I only got the essential. Live at the Village Vanguard: The Master Takes is one disc, makin’ it one-fourth the cost of the box set. And you only get the best stuff.

Man, the opening beauty of “Spiritual…” It’s like a dream I had: I floated on the River Nile, smokin’ some fresh weed, relaxin’. But I ain’t ever gonna see the Nile anyhow. This track’s as close as I come, and it’s close enough. Best of the best, though, has gotta be “India.” It’s only when you listen to a perfect old jazz tune like this that you realize how much drum-n-bass is derived from this music. ‘Trane takes it to heaven and back with some style, man. Some richness, daddy. It’s a sad thing his life was cut short by them jaws o’ death.

Shit, cat. It don’t make a difference. The man produced enough good music to last me a lifetime. This Village Vanguard thing’s just another example of the genius of Coltrane.

posts.com:
I watched Montage of Heck recently. It's a really good documentary, probably the best Nirvana documentary out there. While it helped me understand Cobain better, and I've always liked Nirvana, it also made me feel a tiny bit of disgust at him, which I hadn't felt before. Reason being, he comes across as really un-advanced as a person.

Cobain died when he was 27. He still acted like a teenager. He was always sarcastic and pessimistic, the same way a high school kid acts as a defense mechanism. He doesn't really seem philosophical or insightful. All he mostly talked about was his self-loathing, and he seems very self-absorbed.

He was a great artist - he had a sharp ear for melody, and he constructed perfect, tight little songs. Songwriting (note: that does NOT just mean lyrics) was his strength. But he didn't have much of anything interesting to say.

Aside from basically being an overgrown child, seeing him scabby and strung out with Courtney was depressing. I used to watch a YouTube channel called Soft White Underbelly, which interviews homeless junkies about their lives, and at their worst Kurt and Courtney look just like the people on that channel (example: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FgGW-ivQ8z4). There's nothing romantic about that junkie rockstar lifestyle, if they weren't famous musicians they'd be junkies on the street. I'm glad for them that they weren't.

Brett Morgen, the guy who made this documentary, also made one on David Bowie. The contrast is striking - in his very early 20s Bowie was already insightful, thoughtful, sophisticated, and philosophical. In contrast to Cobain, he was already particularly advanced as a person at a young age.

It doesn't have to be either/or, though. Pete Doherty of The Libertines seems like the halfway point - he was a junkie whose life was a mess, yet he still managed to be insightful, thoughtful, and charming, with lots of interesting things to day. Cobain wasn't - he just mastered writing his songs.

Guitar Player Repair Guide, Erlewine
Build Your Own Electric Guitar, Foley (out of print iirc)
Electronic Projects for Musicians, Anderton (has you build an entire effects rack, but includes guitar wiring)

Anderton's book, I cannot remember much about.

From Genesis to Revelation is Moody Blues-inspired folkpop
Trespass and Nursery Cryme are where they get more proggy but still within the folk realm. A lot more somber in my opinion. Wonderful storytelling. Their most underrated stuff
Foxtrot and Selling England By The Pound is still similar to their other stuff but a lot more theatric (using elements of music hall for example), their classical music inspiration being a lot more upfront as well, and more rock-oriented (psychedelic rock and of course progressive rock), but still within their British folk roots as far as overall sound and storytelling/lyricism goes. This is the fan favorite era.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
IMO The Rolling Stones were better before, but not because of Jones. Jones is great, but early on the Stones were this cool, energetic, stylish, slightly arty blues-rock/R&B band in the London scene, and they were practically a mod band. By the late 60s they'd lost that stylishness, and suddenly their music felt a lot more studied. It all feels perfectly planned out and un-organic. Let It Bleed is a great album, but I don't find it as enjoyable as an album like Out of Our Heads.

This is exactly the opposite from The Beatles IMO, who started out as a pretty lame but very competent pop band, and only really became great when they went psychedelic. So, oddly my opinion of the Beatles rises about the time my opinion of the Stones declines.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114102256
>best amp sim for guitar and/or bass? maybe i'm just retarded but i can't get a good tone out of logic's default ones.
I have used Logic's amps and I found that for a hard rock/metal tone, I needed to do a couple of EQ moves. I think I did this.
1. High shelf boost before the amp.
2. Pretty big mid-scoop after the amp.
3. Pretty big bass boost around 70-100hz, depending on your tuning.
4. High-cut the really bright frequencies, at least above 10k, but possibly even lower than that.
5. You might want a boost around 6k for brightness.
6. Precise notch cuts to dampen resonant frequencies.

Remember that amp sims are really just algorithmic distortion and filters in a box. You can usually get a good tone out of anything with conscious EQ moves.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114125247
I remember the built-in tutorials being decent in 2012. They're probably at least as good now. Sorry I don't have more current info, but here are some very important hotkeys for starters:

>"Tab" switches between horizontal (arrangement) and vertical (session) views
>"Tab" + "Shift" switches between effects view on the bottom and edit view for the selected clip

Also, you'll want to download/install ASIO4ALL if you're on a PC, then set it as your audio driver in the settings menu. It'll help get you lower latency than default Windows drivers.

Last thing - learn where the "record arm" buttons are if you wanna record stuff. In the vertical view, you can click the little record circles for each clip space. If you wanna record to the main timeline, press F9 or click the record button up top. Good luck anon

posts.sub: Mike Love is the true genius of the Beach Boys
posts.com:
You may not know this, but the widely popular song "Revolution 1" from the Beatles' White Album was copied from Mike Love's "Student Demonstration Time".
Mike Love traveled to India with the Beatles in 1968, where he played them his song, which was really appreciated by John Lennon.
Unfortunately, the Beatles ripped him off by releasing "Revolution 1" in the same year, and never gave him credit for it.
Mike is also the original author of "Back in the USSR", which came from him playing "California Girls" to the Beatles during their trip to India. He was once again ripped off, with this song being the opener for the White Album.
Mike Love is one of the most important artists of the 20th century, pioneering many different music genres.
His 1970 song "All I Wanna Do", for instance, is widely regarded as the first dream pop track. Mike was ahead of his time, while Brian Wilson called that song boring.
Most of the Beach Boys' greatest songs were actually written by Mike Love, although Brian Wilson tried to hide this fact by falsely claiming they he had written them on his own. Mike had to sue Wilson in order to be recognized for his creative work.
In conclusion, while most people worship this talentless schizo known as Brian Wilson, the few connoisseurs who actually understand a thing or two about music will recognize the talent of Mike Love, the true genius of the Beach Boys.

Issues is another peak of the band considered by many, it has the same production of Follow The Leader with some influences from Industrial Rock, a lot of emphasis on soundscapes on this one.
Untouchables feels like an extension of this sound, more or less.

posts.com:
>>114102843
Viperman again

>>114102823
Listened to the whole album
That beat drop on track 4 was really good, wasnt expecting that. Those drums and synthd make me think of Orchestral Manouevres at the Dark. Maybe my favorite part of this EP
Vocals are a bit buried in all tracks. Nice bass on track 2. Track 1 isnt really a strong opener to the album I think.
Something about the tracks overall make me not really get into the vibe of the album and engage with it completely. It seems a bit monotonous maybe, like the album is just going through the motions and no part is really different than another. For example, track 2 has a synth solo but when it hapoens everything else (bass, guitar, back synth, drums especially) is just doing the same thing they were already doing. That can be me not being familiar with the style, but I feel the tracks would be better with something to grab the listener. Maybe develop the ideas you have in the arrangement a bit, what I get from it is no moment really standing out. It could help giving some relief (in the architectural sense). Track 3 for example is a bit better in this regard, but even with some cool different synth stuff being introduced the rest of it is still is very much of the same and the vocals being buried doesnt help.
Anyway I like the elements here I just think they could fit together in a better way. Im also not a huge fan of the vague/suggestive lyrics
The final track is a good album closer, maybe the guitar could let itself go a bit tho and play around the synth. But the guitar notes complement the synths really well here

posts.com: If, on the other hand, we estimate the worth of the Beautiful Arts by the culture they supply to the mind, and take as a standard the expansion of the faculties which must concur in the Judgement for cognition, Music will have the lowest place among them (as it has perhaps the highest among those arts which are valued for their pleasantness), because it merely plays with sensations. The formative arts are far before it in this point of view; for in putting the Imagination in a free play, which is also accordant with the Understanding, they at the same time carry on a serious business. This they do by producing a product that serves for concepts as a permanent self-commendatory vehicle for promoting their union with sensibility and thus, as it were, the urbanity of the higher cognitive powers. These two species of art take quite different courses; the first proceeds from sensations to indeterminate Ideas, the second from determinate Ideas to sensations. The latter produce permanent, the former only transitory impressions. The Imagination can recall the one and entertain itself pleasantly therewith; but the other either vanish entirely, or if they are recalled involuntarily by the Imagination they are rather wearisome than pleasant. Besides, there attaches to Music a certain want of urbanity from the fact that, chiefly from the character of its instruments, it extends its influence further than is desired (in the neighbourhood), and so as it were obtrudes itself, and does violence to the freedom of others who are not of the musical company. The Arts which appeal to the eyes do not do this; for we need only turn our eyes away, if we wish to avoid being impressed. The case of music is almost like that of the delight derived from a smell that diffuses itself widely. The man who pulls his perfumed handkerchief out of his pocket attracts the attention of all round him, even against their will, and he forces them, if they are to breathe at all, to enjoy the scent;

I wouldn't necessarily call Toscanini and Furtwangler friends. And they had one big thing in common when it came to Wagner: they were both slow. Strange to think it when Toscanini's reputation as a "fast" conductor precedes him, but his performances at Bayreuth were slower than the historic tradition there. Richard Strauss wasn't happy with either of them.
>>114111683
Toscanini was a very variable conductor like any one else. It's important to realize that we only really know him for the end of his career - that is with the NBC Orchestra and those late 30s-early 50s recordings. He was more critically acclaimed for his tenure with the New York Philharmonic, of which we have far fewer recordings (and the few that we do have are in pretty bad sound). The recordings that are in listenable shape reveal a more flexible conductor, especially outside of classical-era repertoire.

Curious why Vinyl has made a comeback. I grew up with vinyl and switched to CD early in life. I sometimes miss that pop & hiss of playing a record. But I'd really know why anyone chose to return to vinyl after all these years.

I'm actually curious to return but don't know if I can or should. My old collection is gone, I'd have to start from scratch, and I'm not wealthy by any means. And honestly, there were never many albums where I liked EVERY song on an album and skipping to the next track on digital is so ingrained in me now.

So, what advantages do you get by returning to vinyl in terms of listening to them versus cd? Is it really worth the expense? I don't care for "collector's editions" or artwork, and I see WM, Target, etc carrying "exclusives" that I would never feel the need to spend cash for (I just want to listen) and would (I assume) be happier buying actual vintage compared to rereleases on exclusive colored vinyl.

Not hating at all, just for some reason extremely curious and compelled to dive back in (which would be a bit of a financial hardship) and really curios what everyone thinks.

Think about it this way: we've grown into seeing music as a commodity that exists within easy access in an almost immediate fashion. This is great in the sense that anyone can dive into most music, but the issue that's birthed out of that is that your options now outweigh the time you have. It becomes harder to make connections, or to make an investment into a particular music. While vinyl and other physical formats don't cure this new detachment, they at least create an illusion of increased value. you have to physically go out of your way to find it, select it and play it. the music is the same, but the ritual has perhaps elevated the appreciation for it. it's consumerism but it's attempting to asuage our inability to align with our new digital freedoms

posts.name: Anonymous

>>114125196
I've had multiple answers described to me by vinyl listeners, such as:
>if it's older music that was originally released on vinyl, there's an appeal to listen to it on the original format
>finding new music in the cheap bins at record stores is a fun experience to them
>people actually might like the inconveniences of vinyl, and find it relaxing to take in the music once it starts playing
>large album art and colored records make them more interesting to look at compared to CD/digital
>the idea of music being engraved onto a piece of plastic instead of translated from 1s and 0s is seen as a good one. some even hate it if a record was digitally mastered, even if it sounds comparable to analog mastering
Reasons to like vinyl vary greatly on rationality. There's no objective reason to go to vinyl, as enjoyment is purely based on personal preference. At the end of the day, you either like vinyl or don't care for it
